<TEXT>
a us district judge monday barred the state 
from enforcing its yearold antiobscenity law saying the language 
of the statute was unconstitutionally vague 
wisconsin attorney general don hanaway said he would appeal judge 
jp statmuellers ruling to the us circuit court of appeals in 
chicago 
hanaway said he had not seen the decision granting a preliminary 
injunction but he understood the judge ruled it was unclear whether 
the law applied to simulated or actual sexual conduct this was 
not a major issue in the appeal by opponents of the law hanaway 
said 
were going to have an obscenity law that is going to be 
constitutional hanaway said i think it would be wrong for 
people to spend a bunch of money to reopen 
hanaway said he understood some stores had closed following last 
junes enactment of the law which was intended to halt commercial 
traffic in hardcore pornography 
two milwaukee stores denmark book store and paradise video 
store and the pure pleasure ii bookstore in oshkosh filed the 
lawsuit against the state calling the obscenity statute 
unconstitutional 
prosecutors have held off enforcing the law while they awaiting 
statmuellers ruling the law calls for jail terms of up to five 
years and fines of up to 10000 for pornography wholesalers 
under the statute material is obscene if it lacks serious 
literary artistic political educational or scientific value 
stephen m glynn the attorney representing the stores called 
the decision wellreasoned and said were very pleased by it 
but a sponsor of the legislation sen joseph andrea said he was 
disappointed by stadtmuellers decision 
he and sen water j chilsen were very careful when we put this 
the law together to address the constitutional concerns andrea 
said chilsen was the chief sponsor of the bill 
stadtmueller said the law was unconstitutionally vague among 
other issues the judge said it was difficult to determine whether 
the law was violated by pictures or by descriptions of sexually 
explicit conduct or by both 
in addition stadtmueller said the state violated the equal 
protection clause of the constitution by exempting libraries 
schools and universities from prosecution under the statute 
the law would allow a library to commercially distribute obscene 
materials without the threat of prosecution but does not allow an 
adult bookstore to do the same the judge said 
</TEXT>
