<TEXT>
vice president dan quayle said 
sunday he will tell contra commanders this week that if they want to 
lay down arms and return to nicaragua they should be encouraged 
to do so 
the vice president beginning a three day journey to four central 
american countries said however that he will present that only as 
one option the contras might choose as the united states and latin 
heads of state seek a diplomatic rather than military solution to 
the contra war against nicaraguas leftist government 
quayle also indicated he does not have much faith in nicaraguan 
president daniel ortegas promise to hold free elections next 
february as required by the regional peace plan but said e would 
not use those doubts to encourage the contras to hang on for the 
possibility of renewed us military aid 
asked by reporters aboard air force two en route from washington 
whether he would tell the contras to return to nicaragua to 
participate in the political process quayle said im not going to 
do that but im certainly going to lay that out as an option and 
if they feel comfortable they should be encouraged to go back 
he added i dont think it would be proper for me to say this is 
your only option 
quayle is scheduled to meet with a handful of contra field 
commanders on tuesday morning in honduras their 11000member force 
is camped out near the nicaraguan border supplied by us 
nonlethal aid 
quayle said he would underscore the need for the contras to 
refrain from military attacks during this period a condition of the 
us aid package 
he held out hope for fair elections in nicaragua but also voiced 
skepticism attacking ortega and accusing him of already violating 
terms of peace agreements of the contra commanders quayle said i 
dont have to tell them what danny ortegas track record is 
he mentioned specifically us allegations that nicaragua is 
arming leftist rebels in el salvador in violation of the regional 
peace accords 
quayle said the purpose of his trip to guatemala costa rica el 
salvador and honduras is threefold 
to emphasize the importance of democracy in the region 
to get involved on a substantive basis with the presidents 
of those us allies before they and ortega meet again in july to 
further work on their peace plan 
to find out what the presidents think they can to to help 
pressure panamanian leader manuel antonio noriega from power which 
is the bush administrations foremost goal in panama 
quayle was scheduled to meet monday morning with political and 
community leaders in guatemala before seeing president vinicio 
cerezo and then fly on to honduras 
cerezo told reporters last week he expected to discuss a variety 
of topics with quayle including us trade policies and economic 
and military aid the united states has important military and 
economic relationships with each of the countries quayle will visit 
cerezo specifically mentioned as topics of discussion 
us import quotas especially on textiles he said they would 
directly affect the small local textile industry the guatemalan 
government is encouraging 
faster disbursement of 80 million approved in balance of 
payments support for guatemala 
reservations from some congressional quarters about continued 
us military aid 
quayle will be in el salvador for less than a day at a time when 
the country is gripped by a new wave of violence in its nineyear 
civil war his trip is intended in large part to show support for 
the new government of rightist president alfredo cristiani who was 
inaugurated on june 1 
quayle met with cristiani when he was a candidate for president 
in early february and again when cristiani visited washington as 
presidentelect 
cristianis closest adviser cabinet minister jose antonio 
rodriquez porth was gunned down along with two bodyguards on friday 
in an attack cristiani blamed on leftist rebels 
quayle is to deliver the presidents condolences to the rodriquez 
porth family and cristiani 
despite concerns from some on capitol hill and other critics that 
the government of cristianis arena party will give rise to a new 
wave of death squad violence and human rights violations us 
officials have said cristiani deserves a chance to prove his 
prohuman rights statements 
