<TEXT>
with a sharp nononsense crack the gavel in 
the hand of chairman dante fascell hits the desk in the hearing room 
of the house foreign affairs committee 
displaying the bite bark and manner of a grizzled drill 
sergeant the florida democrat is whipping a twoyear 115 million 
foreign assistance bill into shape in long sessions that lasted for 
days 
attendance at meetings is heavy interest is apparently high 
shift the scene to the senate 
chairman claiborne pell dri enters the hearing room of the 
senate foreign relations committee promptly at 10 am and seats 
himself in the center of the horseshoeshaped bench 
the chairs to his right and left are empty 
but pell is determined to get to work on a bill authorizing 45 
billion in spending for the state department and its sister agencies 
pell the gracious selfeffacing possessor of a distinguished 
family heritage dating to colonial times waits patiently for absent 
senators to arrive 
nearly 50 minutes later he shrugs then gloomily announces the 
session cannot proceed for lack of a quorum 
there is he declares wryly a profound lack of interest in 
this bill 
the senate committee on foreign relations once pointed to as a 
summit of legislative prestige influence and power is caught in a 
state of inertia that borders at times on stalemate 
last week the committee floundered through a political dispute 
over a controversial ambassadorial appointment and finally 
surmounting a republican boycott of all its committee meetings 
approved the state department authorization bill 
but even that action left key spending decisions uncertain and 
unresolved 
donald gregg the nominee to be ambassador to south korea is the 
target of a democratic probe of allegations which he denies that 
he used a former position as national security adviser to vice 
president bush to help the illegal resupply of the nicaraguan contra 
rebels 
the gop boycott organized by sen mitch mcconnell rky was 
mounted in the conviction that democrats were attempting to stir 
anew the fading embers of the irancontra affair and sink the gregg 
nomination in a morass of delays and leaks 
mcconnell called off the boycott after sen alan cranston 
dcalif agreed to let the gregg nomination come to a vote on june 
20 
with the gridlock caused by the dispute over gregg cleared away 
the panel was able to consider and approve the state department bill 
but debate was muddied by a tug of war over two competing 
spending priorities the construction in israel of two expensive 
broadcasting transmitters for the voice of america a course 
favored by sen jesse helms rnc and the payment of millions of 
dollars of pastdue payments to the united nations a course favored 
by chairman pell 
the panel decided that the transmitters should be funded but that 
the money should not be taken out of the un account as helms had 
demanded no one said where the money would come from in a foreign 
affairs account that is already nearly 800 million over budget 
ceilings 
the committee tried to return to the larger and more potentially 
controversial foreign aid bill on friday 
but once again no quorum could be mustered 
the panel will try again this week 
many observers say that the panels strongest member is not its 
chairman but helms who as the ranking gop member is the architect 
of his own highly conservative highly anticommunist foreign policy 
pell has held firm against helms determined and imaginative 
tactics and the north carolinian has more than once growled dont 
you try to railroad me mr chairman 
helms fiercely opposed senate ratification of the ussoviet 
mediumrange missile treaty two years ago during the panels 
lengthy consideration of it senior democrats made sure one or all 
of them were present to rebut his assertions and attempt to overcome 
his tactics 
helms also has engaged in a longrunning battle with the state 
department drawing criticism for allegedly delaying diplomatic 
nominations in order to gain leverage in battles to shape foreign 
policy 
the committee many of its critics say has seen brighter days 
the names of such postwar chairman as arthur vandenburg of 
michigan j william fulbright of arkansas and frank church of idaho 
have been central to the shaping of american foreign policy 
the committees influence has been slipping since fulbrights 
chairmanship in the early 1970s with the exception of a brief 
renaissance when sen richard lugar rind headed the panel for 
two years beginning in 1985 
during the lugar years foreignaid legislation marched with 
unaccustomed ease through the congress a consensus was won on 
controversial sanctions against whiteruled south africa and lugar 
helped change us policy toward dictatorial rule in the philippines 
but that was a brighterthanusual period in the committees long 
decline 
over the years other committees have chipped away at the panels 
jurisdiction 
nonmembers often have taken the lead in foreign policy 
initiatives 
and many foreign policy issues now are shaped not in the 
committee but when they reach the senate floor 
