<TEXT>
turning away the case of a marine who died 
after his wisdom tooth was pulled the supreme court today left 
intact a legal doctrine that bars members of the military from suing 
over injuries suffered incident to service 
the court without comment refused to reinstate lawsuits against 
the government by the widow of sgt timothy adkins whose death in 
1985 sparked three separate investigations by the marine corps and 
navy 
according to court records adkins 26 died as a result of 
having his tooth pulled in a dental clinic at the marine corps air 
station in beaufort sc 
the tooth was pulled in june 1985 adkins died aug 8 
the suits filed by his widow gala contend that adkins problems 
began because the technician who assisted in the extraction failed 
to realize that the machine used to sterilize the instruments was 
not working 
adkins developed an infection that was treated unsuccessfully 
with penicillin he was hospitalized in beaufort then transferred 
to the charleston sc naval hospital 
reporting on one investigation into adkins death rear adm john 
fetterman jr inspector general of the navy told sen john glenn 
dohio the ultimate responsibility must be borne by a system 
which allowed nonphysician health care providers to admit a patient 
on the serious list and schedule and perform subsequent surgery 
without a medical evaluation by a credentialed physician 
fetterman added sgt adkins was transferred to charleston 
so that a more sophisticated level of care could be delivered and 
this did not occur 
mrs adkins lawsuits were dismissed reluctantly last year by 
us district judge falcon hawkins in charleston who cited a 1950 
supreme court decision shielding the government from lawsuits by 
injured military personnel 
that decision in a case called feres vs us and its sequels 
is known today as the feres doctrine 
it is difficult to imagine a case less ripe for dismissal than 
one in which adkins died after having a tooth pulled but feres 
and its progeny tie the courts hands judge hawkins said 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals upheld his dismissal last 
feb 2 
in the appeal acted on today the justices were urged to use 
adkins case to overrule or limit the application of the feres 
doctrine 
it should be noted that this case involves dental and medical 
care under domestic peacetime conditions the appeal said 
it is to say the least not easy to kill someone by pulling 
their tooth it added the sequence of events flowing from the 
removal of sgt adkins tooth and culminating in his paralysis coma 
and eventual death required the malfeasance misfeasance and 
nonfeasance of medical health care providers from three separate 
military installations 
the supreme court last upheld the feres doctrine in a 1987 
decision in which the justices voted 54 to bar families of military 
personnel killed on duty from suing negligent federal employees who 
took part in the military mission 
led by justice antonin scalia the four dissenters called the 
1950 feres decision a mistake that has caused unfairness and 
irrationality 
the courts fivemember majority in the 1987 case included 
nowretired justice lewis f powell whose seat was filled in 1988 
by justice anthony m kennedy 
congress has considered various amendments to the feres doctrine 
which some members have contended treats members of the armed 
services as second class citizens 
the case is adkins vs us 881776 
