<TEXT>
the supreme court today made it easier to 
recover lawyers fees for people who win disputes with the 
government over social security benefits 
by a 54 vote the court said the government must reimburse legal 
fees incurred during administrative proceedings that a federal court 
has ordered the department of health and human services to conduct 
the decision is a victory for elmer hudson an alabama woman who 
won disability benefits in a dispute with the government 
justice sandra day oconnor in her opinion for the court said 
requiring the award of legal fees in such cases is in keeping with a 
federal law the equal access to justice act giving lawyers an 
incentive to represent the needy 
the law demands reimbursement of legal fees for more than just 
court proceedings she said 
we find it difficult to ascribe to congress an intent to throw 
the social security claimant a lifeline that it knew was a foot 
short said oconnor 
she was joined by justices william j brennan thurgood marshall 
harry a blackmun and john paul stevens 
dissenting were chief justice william h rehnquist and justices 
byron r white antonin scalia and anthony m kennedy 
white in an opinion joined by the other dissenters said the 
court misread the law 
our duty is to apply statutes as they were enacted by congress 
not to take it upon ourselves to overcome the political realities 
that blocked what we might consider to be good legislation he 
said 
the case began when mrs hudson filed a social secuirty 
disability claim in september 1981 she said a variety of physical 
and emotional ailments prevented her from continuing to work as a 
maid and janitor 
an administrative law judge of the health and human services 
agency denied her claim ruling that none of mrs hudsons ailments 
was so severe as to render her disabled 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals overruled the decision in 
1985 the appeals court said mrs hudsons impairments must be 
considered in combination and sent the case back to the health and 
human services agency 
an administrative law judge then determined she was disabled 
since may 1981 and granted her benefits 
the 11th circuit court last year said the government now must 
reimburse mrs hudson for attorneys fees she incurred during the 
second round of administrative proceedings 
the former reagan administration before it left office in 
january asked the supreme court to reverse the appeals court ruling 
justice department lawyers argued that the administrative 
proceedings ordered by the 11th circuit court were not adversarial 
in the way that court proceedings are and therefore said legal fees 
should not be recoverable 
the case is sullivan vs hudson 88616 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

