<TEXT>
a study has found that nearly all 
nonsmokers have traces of a nicotine derivative in their systems 
most of them from exposdure to smoke at work and in public places 
scientists said monday 
that indicates restrictions on public smoking can reduce the 
threat of smoke to nonsmokers they said 
nearly all the 663 nonsmokers in the 1986 study had traces of a 
nicotine derivative in their urine said researchers at roswell park 
memorial institute 
this means they had had a recent exposure to tobacco smoke 
said dr k michael cummings who conducted the study what that 
means is exposure to tobacco smoke among nonsmokers at least in 
the western new york area is ubiquitous 
the percentage of smokers in the buffalo area is about the 
national average meaning the studys findings should be reflective 
of the country as a whole cummings said 
studies have linked passive smoke exposure to a wide range of 
health problems including eye and nose irritation respiratory 
infections in infants and children and increased risks of heart 
disease and cancer 
cummings said 91 percent of the buffaloarea nonsmokers 
interviewed over a year had traces of cotinine a breakdown product 
of nicotine in their urine 
what surprised researchers is that only 76 percent of the 
nonsmokers reported they had been exposed to tobacco smoke in the 
four days previous to the study 
even among those individuals who did not live with a smoker 
84 percent had evidence of cotinine in their urine which was 
indicative of exposures probably occurring outside the home 
cummings said 
in the study researchers interviewed nonsmoking volunteers who 
had gone to roswell park as part of a cancer screening clinic 
combining the 28 percent who said their exposure to smoke came at 
work with the 16 those who said their exposure came in restaurants 
and 8 percent in public buildings cummings said more than half of 
the reported exposures occurred in areas where nonsmokers dont 
have the option of avoiding the exposure 
these findings suggest that policies regulating smoking in 
public places could have a significant impact on reducing a persons 
exposure to environmental tobacco smoke said cummings 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

