<TEXT>
the pentagon office that oversees star wars 
research said monday it had signed an agreement with britains 
ministry of defense to launch a joint computer project 
the work valued at an estimated 26 million over the next 4 
years will involve development and demonstration of socalled 
knowledgebased computer systems the pentagon said 
knowledgebased software programs are capable of learning and 
expanding their own capabilities as new information is added to the 
original programmed data the work with britain will focus on how 
such computer systems might help operate a defensive system against 
battlefield or naval missiles 
for example software intended to facilitate identification of 
a particular type of missile body from its rocket plume signature 
could learn to accomplish the same task for different types of 
missiles given only the new plume signature data the pentagon 
said 
the strategic defense initiative organization the pentagons 
star wars office said the british had agreed to pick up 58 percent 
of the projects cost and the united states would pick up the 
remaining 42 percent 
