more american wetlands could be saved through 
tax breaks and other incentives than through regulations a group of 
senators told environmental protection agency administrator william 
k reilly monday 
reilly and new jersey gov thomas kean chairman of the national 
wetlands policy forum met with nine senators to discuss strategies 
for stemming the loss of americas shrinking wetlands 
the administration previously thought it would confine itself 
to executive orders said sen john h chafee rri you do 
better with incentives he said after the meeting 
you get a lot more with a carrot than a stick kean said of 
the incentive approach that might be offered to farmers developers 
and private landowners to encourage actions that would help protect 
if not increase swamps estuaries and other watersoaked land that 
protects wildlife cleans waterways and helps regulate streamflow 
more than 50 percent of tidal wetlands in the lower 48 states is 
in private hands senators conveyed their concern that federal 
wetlands policy be fair to landowners kean said 
a lot of senators wanted to make sure this wasnt a 
confiscatory policy kean said we want to make sure for those 
areas where wetlands are acquired they receive full compensation 
he said 
senators such as james a mcclure ridaho said environmental 
policymakers might work from the example of historic preservation 
programs which have been based upon tax breaks for those who 
rehabilitate buildings to strict federal standards chafee said 
the 20member national wetland policy forum made up of state and 
local officials farmers businessmen developers and academic 
experts returned a set of more than 100 recommendations last fall 
aimed at achieving no net loss of wetlands president bush 
endorsed such a goal in the campaign 
no one is certain but there have been estimates that up to 
400000 acres of wetlands have been lost to development annually in 
recent years 
the forum was convened with the help of the conservation 
foundation which reilly headed before being named epa chief 
