a man castrated by two masked men before he was 
convicted of raping a teenage girl has evidence for a new trial 
his attorney told a federal appeals court monday 
the case against wayne dumond of forrest city ark was an 
absolute failure of justice attorney john wesley hall told a 
threejudge panel of the 8th us circuit court of appeals 
dumond convicted in 1985 of raping and kidnapping the forrest 
city teen is serving a prison sentence of life plus 20 years 
hall said dumond deserved an opportunity to question the girl 
regarding new genetic evidence the attorney said proved his client 
could not have committed the rape 
last january us magistrate h david young in little rock ark 
denied dumonds request for a new trial and motions to subpoena the 
victim and her father 
young said the victims identification of dumond was strong and 
that the newly discovered evidence of an inconclusive scientific 
test would not likely produce a verdict of acquittal upon retrial 
hall contended monday that it was necessary to question the 
victim in connection with new genetic evidence derived from semen 
found on her pant leg 
hall said the genetic test proved dumond could not have committed 
the rape and that the procedure was more than 99 percent accurate 
the attorney also claimed the victims initial identification of 
dumond was shaky and that she was coached by her father in picking 
dumond out of a lineup 
assistant attorney general theodore holder said he had moved to 
quash the subpoenas so the victim would not be put through further 
painful testimony 
holder said her testimony would not have changed 
her identification was solid he said she never varied 
while dumond was awaiting trial two masked men broke into his 
home and bound and castrated him no arrests have been made in that 
case 
