maximilian robespierres own draft of the french 
constitution and one of the guillotines he kept busy until he lost 
his own head in 1794 were sold at auction monday 
the constitution sold for 44000 and auctioneer jacques tajan 
said it would be placed in the permanent collection of the national 
assembly library 
the last item in the sale held at the drouot auction house in 
central paris was a guillotine dating to revolutionary france a 
german collector who asked to remain anonymous bought it for 
40000 the auction house reported 
the 57page manuscript of the draft of the constitution contains 
notes by robespierre on aspects of the first constitution prepared 
in 1791 by the national assembly 
other items auctioned included documents from the bloody events 
of 200 years ago they included papers relating to king louis xvis 
trial that led to his conviction for treason and subsequent 
execution at the guillotine 
the guillotine whose use was advocated by dr joseph guillotin 
during the french revolution in preference to less humane methods 
was first used in 1792 
a twopage handwritten letter dated oct 10 1789 from queen 
marie antoinette to the austrian ambassador in paris was bought 
19000 by a french collector who also asked to remain anonymous 
it describes the queens departure from the palace at versailles 
four days earlier and declares her belief that the bourgeoisie and 
the people were on her side and would prevail even though they 
were weaker than the revolutionaries 
all the texts of marieantoinettes correspondance are in the 
archives in vienna but most of the original letters have 
disappeared said jean chalon author of a recent biography of the 
austrianborn queen 
this is a rare look at marieantoinette and you can be sure 
its an original because its full of spelling mistakes 
known as the incorruptible robespierre sent some 17000 
people to the guillotine during the yearlong reign of terror that 
came to a climax with his own beheading in 1794 
his notes in the constitutional draft show that he opposed 
creation of a legislative branch composed of representatives elected 
by the people 
his notes also oppose the national assemblys plan to limit the 
vote to those paying taxes worth three days work 
wealth corrupts more than poverty robespierre wrote in the 
margin of the text millionaires are the ones who should be 
