editors note when he won the van cliburn competition in fort 
worth texas in 1973 it seemed that the world of vladimir viardo 
had changed forever but it led to a musical odyssey that found him 
back in the soviet union locked away from western audiences now he 
seems to have found a happy ending 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
one night in a ukrainian village vladimir viardo 
was playing a chopin barcarole when he noticed cockroaches crawling 
out of the keyboard even more disconcerting was the horse and cart 
that failed to negotiate a uturn on the road outside the hall and 
crashed through a window and onto the stage 
that was during the 13 years when viardo was forbidden to leave 
the eastern bloc before he became the first soviet artist to be 
allowed to move to the west with his family while retaining his 
citizenship 
this spring viardo played a very different venue at carnegie 
hall he punctuated his concert by pounding his fist on the keyboard 
of a steinway grand piano sweeping it across the keys to a bass 
note and an electrifying ovation 
for years i collected rage and i could hit he says once 
youve tasted freedom you dont want to be subdued anymore 
in december he moved into a new york apartment with his wife and 
two sons with the approval of the soviet government unlike many 
of his colleagues he did not defect and continues to perform in his 
native land 
i didnt want to leave forever russian nostalgia is a very 
strong feeling says the 39yearold pianist in fluent 
slavicaccented english 
but the pull of the new world particularly texas is equally 
strong 
i have such a special feeling for texas such tenderness he 
says it is a sort of native land for me i spiritually recognize 
it 
it was there in fort worth that viardos us career began in 
1973 when his musical panache and vast technical arsenal carried 
him to victory in the van cliborn competition a twoyear tour of 
the west ensued but on the eve of a 1976 us trip soviet 
officials canceled all his foreign engagements one by one over 
three weeks without an explanation 
for years viardos performances were confined to the soviet 
union and a few east bloc countries most of his 80 yearly concerts 
were played in the biggest halls on the best pianos and he was 
wellknown to soviet audiences but he also brought music to the 
farmers sometimes having to fix broken hammers in pianos before he 
could perform 
the inner world was the only escape for me in the soviet 
union says viardo i lost friends because i did not participate 
in the political system i was broken spiritually but my music was 
really better after that because i used this pressure for artistic 
purposes 
in moscow he says when i felt very lonely i played a cycle 
of loneliness the schubert songs transcribed by liszt it was 
public loneliness on the stage 
then came the 1980s and soviet president mikhail gorbachevs 
policy of glasnost or openness viardo was allowed to travel 
abroad twice to play in western europe in the summer of 1987 and 
again in the summer of 1988 when he replaced an ailing soviet 
emigre pianist with the los angeles philharmonic at the hollywood 
bowl 
the big break came in the fall of 1988 when he was on a tour of 
europe south africa argentina and the united states he was 
offered an artistinresidence position at the university of north 
texas in denton 
his old friends from texas had never forgotten him visiting 
moscow repeatedly working to bring him back and as he traveled on 
a highway between dallas and fort worth a childs feeling 
induced him to stay 
the political structure in russia was changing and i thought 
this is the right moment viardo recalls i did not bring my 
music my books or even much underwear but i said why not 
he wrote a letter to the soviet ambassador in washington asking 
that his wife natasha be allowed to bring their children to the 
united states four nervous weeks later the soviets granted what he 
calls oral permission for his sons to leave the soviet union 
natasha viardo and sons philipp 12 and alexander 5 left 
moscow for new york on dec 11 gorbachev was to be in new york that 
day and viardo calculated that the soviets would not block his 
familys exit because they would not want to cause their leader any 
embarrassment 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890612-0207 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the exit came off without a hitch though viardo notes that the 
soviets have never provided a written guarantee that his family can 
continue to stay outside the soviet union and keep their citizenship 
the us government also did not give the viardos free rein 
after viardo met with president ronald reagan and secretary of state 
george shultz the us government gave him a visa so he could teach 
at the university of north texas twice a month until 1990 
but viardo cannot travel beyond a 25mile radius of any american 
city and he must make a special request for every tour within the 
united states and he must reapply for his work permit each time he 
returns from abroad 
still he feels much more free with selfexpression in the west 
i felt myself getting rotten playing all the time with the same 
soviet orchestras 
the pianist says he wants his musicmaking to be bigger and 
higher up than the mechanics of the instrument 
i am not interested only in piano playingi have to be in 
love with piecesi am in love now with the second shostakovich 
sonata madly in love i feel that the open painful touches suit 
me 
in april viardo seduced the carnegie hall audience with a 
program of sonatas by domenico scarlatti rachmaninoffs corelli 
variations and debussys impressionistic preludes 
to end the program the pianist offered the american premiere of 
some theater music by the 20thcentury soviet composer dimitri 
shostakovich viardo played the bedbug like a broadway showman 
his fingers prancing on the keys with what he calls deadly humor 
and a wry smile but he says the general feeling of the program was 
of slowly sliding from the roof and struggling to keep yourself 
up not knowing if youll fall off 
the rachmaninoff and the scarlatti are united by a concealed 
pain he says the 19thcentury russian composers piece alludes 
to his impending death and the 18thcentury italian composer 
reflects on his unrequited love for a student 
rachmaninoff is for me nostalgic he went abroad after the 1917 
bolshevik revolution and suffered because he was not able to be in 
russia 
next season viardo is scheduled to return to the soviet union 
for concerts followed by an american tour with the moscow 
philharmonic but these dates were arranged before he brought his 
sons to the united states since then there have been no new offers 
of concerts in the soviet union 
viardo was born in the village of krasnaya polyana he received 
his first piano lessons at age 6 from his grandmother a former 
stalinist camp inmate who took care of him while his mother a 
pianist and singer was touring 
my mama told me ill throw you into the water like a puppy 
when she sent him to music school in moscow at the age of 14 at 
first he says he had little money he slept in railroad cars in a 
depot each night 
it didnt upset me not at all because lots of spiritual 
things were going on the greatest experience was to go to the 
conservatory he says 
he received a doctorate from the conservatory in 1975 and taught 
there until last year in may he performed at the school as part of 
a tour that included stops in france belgium and israel 
his success notwithstanding the move to the united states has 
not been an easy one i had a very heavy period in new york it 
was very hard with the psychological changesive become a 
different animal here he feels he must accelerate events make 
up for lost time 
although he has received rave reviews from american critics for 
his poised lyricism lucid tone and flashy pyrotechnics viardo 
admits he needs more concerts to build a fasttrack western career 
and viardo says he sometimes misses his moscow life and friends 
his dacha his five pianos and his native caucasian mountains 
ask him if he is happy and he will demur 
happiness in the russian interpretation is something you will 
never reach he says still he is happy to have a piano and a 
studio happy to have a contented family happy to travel and to 
meet people 
most of all i am always happy when i hear my colleagues 
playing well and playing from the heart and touching the sky i 
start to physically perspire to jump it makes me really out of my 
mind 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

