<DOCNO> AP890612-0214 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
this is a town that surrendered its name 
to a deadly disease and signaled to the world what unchecked 
industrial waste can do to humans wildlife and their surroundings 
more than 800 of its citizens paid the price in death and 
thousands more have been left painfully crippled 
in the beginning people were left puzzled by the scourge wrought 
by a chemical companys indiscriminate dumping of mercury into 
minamata bay 
it was 1950 and they saw fish floating belly up birds dropping 
into the sea and cats dancing in wild death convulsions 
then in 1956 they themselves began to feel it hands and feet 
going numb tunnel vision a loss of coordination and balance 
chronic pain convulsions and in many cases death 
until then minamata had been a bustling fishing and factory town 
nestled between lush green rice paddies and orange groves in far 
southwestern japan the clear blue waters of its scenic harbor 
yielded abundant seafood 
shinobu sakamoto and her older sister mayumi were among the 
first to become victims of what much later would be called minamata 
disease 
mayumi died in 1956 at age 5 
shinobu who was born in 1956 was poisoned while in her mothers 
womb she is one of some 60 second generation victims born with 
severe defects 
some evenings shinobu wanders into the soushisha a cooperative 
set up to help poisoning victims to visit watch television and 
sometimes to spend the night in the large strawmat room where 
visitors stay 
she speaks and walks with difficulty but is cheerful 
the poisoning in minamata was caused by mercuryladen water 
discharged by a factory owned by the chemical company chisso corp 
the pollution devastated the town 
its population which was 50000 in 1956 has dropped to 36000 
and continues to fall while the number of poisonrelated deaths has 
climbed to 871 by local count 
all told about 200000 people in minamata and its surrounding 
villages on the southwestern island of kyushu were affected in one 
way or another by the poisoning 
the factory that polluted minamatas harbor once employed 5000 
people it now hires only 700 many of its buldings stand empty in 
the fenced chisso compound grim monuments to a disaster 
minamatas victims and their supporters speak of their tragedy as 
a classic case of the high cost of japans industrialization 
people just care about money and what it buys said takanori 
goto a tokyo lawyer who has represented some of the victims in 
court theyre not concerned about the victims created by 
industrial prosperity minamata is a typical example 
chisso corp whose acetaldehydeprocessing factory began dumping 
an estimated total of 27 tons of mercury into minamata bay in 1932 
denied responsibility for the pollution which continued until 1968 
minamata and several other severe outbreaks of industrial 
poisoning led the government to establish an environment agency in 
1970 but the victims have faced lengthy court battles to gain 
compensation for their suffering 
as the victims grow older the average age of first generation 
victims is 60 they continue their battles in court and also 
negotiate with chisso which is has paid so much in compensation 
that it is basically insolvent lawyer goto said 
of the 12296 people who have applied for official designation as 
minamata disease victims the health and welfare ministry has 
granted only 2210 the official recognition that would provide them 
with compensation welfare assistance and medical care 
we believe at least 10 to 20 percent of the 200000 people 
living in the affected area have symptoms of the poisoning said 
teruo kawamoto 57 a minamata disease victim who has led battles 
with chisso for more than 20 years 
in my case i suffer from a bad heart numb hands and feet i 
have liver trouble headaches and back pain i dont really expect 
to win but im determined to keep on trying to help those people 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

