<TEXT>
with a 112billion foreign debt 1000 percent 
and economic stagnation brazil is unable to keep up with its needs 
for public health care and people are dying needlessly says one 
medical official this is one of a series of periodic reports by the 
associated press on the economic social and political turbulence 
that has turned south america into a continent in crisis 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a critically ailing economy and a 
failure to allot funds have crippled brazils health care system 
public hospitals are unable to give proper care to patients they 
admit and often are forced to turn away the sick and injured for 
lack of staff beds medicines money and equipment even in 
emergency cases 
many deaths one official says thousands have been attributed 
to the crisis 
at the same time diseases long under control elsewhere in the 
world tuberculosis yellow fever polio and malaria have made 
their way back to brazil according to the united nationsaffiliated 
world health organization 
in addition waves of strikes by doctors nurses and workers for 
better pay further hobble a system that was never at its best to 
begin with public health doctors earn the equivalent of only 130 a 
month 
we are in the midst of an unprecedented health care crisis that 
is causing the needless deaths of thousands of brazilians said 
dr laerte andrade vaz de mello president of rio de janeiro states 
regional medical council 
brazil the worlds seventh largest industrial power has one of 
the worlds highest infant mortality rates and ranks third worldwide 
in the number of aids cases 
parasitic diseases are rampant malnutrition is common 
public hospitals are overcrowded understaffed illequipped and 
poorly stocked doctors nurses and staff are on strike more than 
half the working year public hospitals in major cities lack 
ambulances to reach outlying slum districts where the poor live 
some examples of tragic cases as turned up in state and city 
medical investigations 
doctors in brazils largest emergency center in rio de janeiro 
turned away a 19yearold motorcyclecrash victim with a skull 
fracture because all of its 12 operating rooms were in use and not 
enough doctors were on duty at the time anyway two hours later the 
victim died according to rio de janeiros municipal medical council 
seven overcrowded rio hospitals refused to admit a man suffering 
from a severe concussion for lack of room fourteen hours later the 
man slipped into a coma and died en route to an eighth hospital the 
rio state medical council said 
in sao paulo the wife of a former congressman benedito cintra 
in need of an emergency caesarean section died because the only 
anesthesiologist on duty was involved in an operation on another 
floor and could not get to her in time 
the government tottering under a 112 billion foreign debt 
1000 percent annual inflation and negative economic growth 
contributes just 4 percent of overall revenue to health care 
its frightening dr ana maria litke secretary general of 
brazils national medical council told the ap but life just 
isnt worth that much here 
further straining the health care system is the mass of people 
who have poured into city slums from the impoverished countryside 
meanwhile eight government ministries squabble over authority to 
grant funds for health care to states and cities delays sometimes 
as long as three months often cause hospital strikes and shutdowns 
by the time money trickles down to the city level little is 
usually left said antonio de carvalho rios deputy health 
secretary 
still brazil spent billions of dollars in the 1970s to become a 
world exporter of specialized hospital technology 
our priorities are out of whack said dr sergio arouca 
president of the national doctors union were building hospitals 
in other countries and our own doctors are being paid bluecollar 
wages 
public health doctors are forced to moonlight as truck drivers 
and policemen nurses take home less than 64 a month the minimum 
wage and many supplement their wages by selling homemade items in 
street markets 
recently doctors nurses and staff workers in rio de janeiro 
went on a fivemonth strike paralyzing city hospitals 
in one incident health officials asked gov wellington moreira 
franco to cancel the worldfamous prelent carnival in rio de 
janeiro because not enough doctors or staff would be available to 
handle the increased number of injuries that occur over the fourday 
period only then did the government rush in 5 million in emergency 
relief to staff emergency wards 
in march federal hospitals in brasilia the capital cancelled a 
third of their surgery cases because of a shortage of linens and 
blankets at the same time in sao paulo the nations largest city 
and main medical center more than 90 percent of private hospitals 
shut down during a strike 
even rio de janeiros national cancer institute the nations top 
public institution closed six of 10 operating rooms because of a 
40day delay in government funding 
shortages of medical supplies lead to rationing hoarding and in 
some cases black marketing 
unscrupulous private dealers often buy blood from beggars and 
prostitutes and resell it at a profit without testing for aids or 
other diseases more than 60 percent of about 6 million transfusions 
done each year involve untested blood according to the health 
ministry 
even human organs are for sale although it is illegal 
classified ads appear daily in newspapers for corneas kidneys and 
livers 
proponents of health care reform are pushing congress for a 
single health ministry to administer funds regionalized health 
networks a national health care fund reequipping of hospitals 
and construction of clinics in remote rural areas 
brazils new constitution approved by congress in october 
guarantees this type of health care reform said jose noronha 
health secretary of rio de janeiro state 
but reform would mean cutting thousands of workers from the 
government payroll a touchy issue most politicans would rather 
avoid with a presidential election set for november 
were up against a wall of civil servants who wont be happy to 
lose their jobs noronha said 
the national outcry has produced a flurry of political squabbles 
but little action most health officials blame the inactivity on 
savage individualism and moral decadence they maintain is 
running deep through the country 
brazilians are solely out for themselves said dr valdir 
cuna goncalves a respected cancer specialist why expect the 
governments attitude to be any different 
but some like dr litke of the national health council remain 
optimistic 
brazil has the capacity to resurrect its health care system 
she said its a matter of when people decide theyve had enough 
suffering 
