<TEXT>
uncontrolled settlement in brazils 
amazon rain forest has led to an alarming spread of a centuriesold 
scourge of the tropics malaria 
as hundreds of thousands of prospectors farmers and adventurers 
poured into brazils vast northern wilderness in the past decade 
many fell victim to the mosquitoborne disease 
last year the health ministry registered 560000 cases of 
malaria in brazil up from 500000 a year before the number is 
expected to rise again this year 
to control the outbreak the health ministry plans a massive 
spraying campaign with ddt an insecticide banned in many countries 
only shock treatment can contain the spread of malaria in 
amazonia dr agostinho cruz marquez head of the health 
ministrys malaria division said in an interview 
malaria is almost exclusively a problem of amazonia a 2 million 
squaremile wilderness sprawled across northern and western brazil 
of the 560000 cases last year 97 percent were in the amazon states 
of amazonas para rondonia and acre 
the worst affected is rondonia a state the size of oregon on 
brazils western border with bolivia and notorious for the 
destruction of its rain forest rondonia had 42 percent of the 
countrys malaria cases with 192 deaths in the first eight months of 
1988 
the goldmining town of ariquemes in rondonia has become the 
world capital of malaria cruz marquez said 
the military government that ruled from 1964 to 1985 urged poor 
brazilians to settle in the undeveloped amazon using slogans such 
as the brave march to the west since the drive began in the 
1970s the incidence of malaria has risen more than 500 percent 
malaria causes fever and chills and a gradual debilitation of the 
body it can be fatal if not treated in brazil 1 to 2 percent of 
those who get the disease die from it cruz marquez said 
although quininebased drugs can cure malaria in 24 hours the 
government cannot get the medicine to all who need it throughout the 
vast and often inaccessible wilderness he added 
the federation of miners says an estimated 3000 mining sites in 
amazonia have drawn untold thousands of prospectors shopkeepers 
pilots and prostitutes to remote areas often the only access is by 
helicopter or small planes which land on dirt strips 
to attend to this population the governments public health 
campaign department has just 300 laboratories cruz marquez said 
adding that in some mining sites a swedishmade malaria drug called 
larian that enters the country as contraband is sold literally for 
the price of gold 
now he said the government plans to send 70000 army soldiers 
to the region to begin the antimalaria campaign 
cruz marquez said ddt would be used because of its low cost and 
effectiveness against the marlariacarrying anopheles mosquito 
the insecticide will not be used indiscriminately but only to 
spray inside the huts and leantos used by miners and settlers he 
said 
the fiveyear campaign will cost 198 million and will be paid 
for in part with loans from the world bank cruz marquez said 
malaria is the only thing that scares a prospector he said 
in a way its a giant shield of defense for the amazon 
</TEXT>
