<TEXT>
if the first concern of going to college is high tuition cost 
then the next is financing it especially if your income is too high 
to qualify for federally supported loans 
supplemental loans privately financed often with institutional 
connections often can fill the gap and are available when other 
sources are not 
in the case of parents who have more than one child going to 
college its often difficult to pull together the necessary funds 
from savings or monthly income to cover tuition payments says 
diane l saunders spokesperson for the nonprofit new england 
education loan marketing corporation or nellie mae this is where 
supplemental loan programs can help greatly 
similar to business and personal loans supplementals are based 
on credit not need sponsors include state agencies nonprofit 
corporations lending organizations and colleges and universities 
either individually or through cooperative consortiums financing is 
through bond issues or other private sources 
higher loan limits and longer repayment schedules than federal 
loans characterize most of them interest rates are higher than the 
federal loans but still lower than personal or consumer loans many 
offer options to pay interest only during the students enrollment 
deferring the principal 
some of the supplementals can be found only in particular areas 
though others offer help nationally and can be used at any 
accredited college or university 
public libraries boards or departments of education guidance 
counselors and the universities themselves can help you locate a 
supplemental loan program one of the best sources is the college 
or university at which the student has been accepted says ms 
saunders 
she adds that nellie mae offers supplemental loan programs for 
both undergraduate and postgraduate students called excel and share 
for more information contact nellie mae at 50 braintree hill park 
suite 300 braintree mass 021841763 
