<TEXT>
as the dollar has surged upward in foreign 
exchange of late many people in the financial world have been 
cheering it on 
if there were no emotions involved their response might well be 
less exuberant many economists are busy right now drawing up lists 
of the hazards as well as the benefits that a rising dollar poses 
for instance a prospective loss of competitive edge in the global 
marketplace 
but there are emotions involved a nations currency in many ways 
symbolizes its strength or weakness and the confidence or lack of 
confidence that its people might be entitled to feel 
some observers also hail the dollars gains as tangible evidence 
that rival ideas specifically communism to the united states 
capitalist system are being put to flight 
lenin is said to have declared that the best way to destroy the 
capitalist system was to debauch the currency the eminent 
economist john maynard keynes wrote in 1931 
by a continuing process of inflation governments can 
confiscate secretly and unobserved an important part of the wealth 
of their citizenslenin was certainly right 
in the last 25 years or so american currency has taken a lot of 
punches though it has evaded any knockout blows it certainly has 
been bruised 
a penny saved is no longer a penny earned in the late 1980s a 
penny saved is pointless 
even if inflation in this country remains at only 5 percent 
the wall street journal notes in less than three decades a dollar 
will have shrunk to a quarter in purchasing power 
nevertheless such scary images pale beside the economic 
nightmare now unfolding in argentina 
that nations inflation rate is projected at something like 
12000 percent this year propelling it to the brink of calamity 
our money is worthless a worker at the national mint told a new 
york times reporter 
the dollars strong showing and argentinas woes have provided a 
new platform for monetarism a school of economic thought that 
emphasizes the importance of the amount of money circulating through 
the system 
inflation monetarists contend is not caused by droughts or oil 
embargoes or other such events it results from too much growth in 
the supply of money 
if a country like argentina didnt exist monetarists would 
have to invent it just to have a laboratory in which to prove their 
theories says norman fosback editor of the financial advisory 
letter market logic in fort lauderdale fla 
in the last 14 years the us money supply expanded about 
3fold argentinas money supply by comparison expanded more than 
3 millionfold in the same period 
over the last year by some measures money supply growth as 
managed by the federal reserve in this country has been virtually 
nil to some observers that and the dollars recent rise mean an 
increasing risk of recession 
the coming downturn will be exacerbated by the federal 
reserves supertight monetary policy contends erich heinemann 
chief economist at the investment firm of ladenburg thalmann amp co 
with a continued rise in the dollar heinemann says the growth 
of exports should slow to a crawl the more the dollar goes up the 
bigger the risk the us will slide into a recession 
but fosback for one doesnt agree in stark contrast to the 
argentinian example he says we think recent careful control of 
us money supply will soon be reflected in declining inflation and 
enhanced longterm prosperity 
</TEXT>
